"There has been a rush over the last few years for companies, educational institutions and law firms to connect their internal computer networks into the Internet and other online services. These activities have been driven by the increased use of electronic mail and the Internet. While many organizations carefully monitor what documents and other materials employees seek: to remove from the workplace, far fewer monitor what information is sent from or received by the company electronically. However, a growing body of case law indicates that there are a number of areas in which an organizations may face potentially enormous liability for the online activities of its employees. While a company cannot pull the plug on its connection to the Net, or monitor all communications taking place online, it can take reasonable steps to lower the risk that the company will be held liable for the improper (and sometimes illegal) conduct of its employees. These steps include the development of a comprehensive written corporate policy on proper Internet usage and an educational programme to train employees in what conduct is either permissible or impermissible."
